  "footnotes": [
    "Heptarchy (c.500–927): the seven major Anglo-Saxon kingdoms — Northumbria, Mercia, East Anglia, Wessex, Essex, Sussex, and Kent — competed for dominance (bretwalda); Wessex under Alfred the Great (871–899) resisted Viking invasion and his grandson Æthelstan unified England by conquering the last Viking stronghold of York in 927",
    "Danelaw (865–954): following the Great Heathen Army's invasion, eastern and northern England came under Scandinavian law and settlement; the cultural impact was profound — English absorbed thousands of Norse words (law, sky, they, window) and the Danelaw's administrative divisions (ridings, wapentakes) persisted for centuries",
    "Norman Conquest (1066): William the Conqueror's victory at Hastings replaced the Anglo-Saxon aristocracy wholesale; the Domesday Book (1086) documented England's resources; Norman French became the language of court and law, creating the dual vocabulary characteristic of modern English (beef/cow, pork/pig, court/yard)",
    "Angevin Empire (1154–1216): at its height under Henry II, the Plantagenet domains stretched from Scotland to the Pyrenees, including England, Normandy, Anjou, Aquitaine, and Brittany; this was a feudal confederation rather than a centralized state, and most of the French territories were lost under King John by 1214",
    "Kingdom of Ireland (1541–1800): Henry VIII declared himself King of Ireland, beginning centuries of English/British rule; successive plantations (particularly Ulster, 1606) displaced the native Catholic population; the Penal Laws (1695–1829) systematically excluded Catholics from political and economic life",
    "Acts of Union (1707 & 1800): the 1707 Act merged the English and Scottish parliaments to create Great Britain, driven partly by Scotland's financial crisis after the Darien Scheme; the 1800 Act incorporated Ireland after the 1798 rebellion, creating the United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland",
    "Great Famine (1845–1852): the potato blight devastated Ireland, killing approximately 1 million and forcing another 1 million to emigrate; Ireland's population fell from 8.2 million (1841) to 6.6 million (1851) and continued declining to 4.4 million by 1911; the famine radicalized Irish nationalism and fueled the diaspora"
  ]
}
